english:
  title: A Letter to Jon Jeon Ryeo-ji
  author: Lee Gyeo-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I write to you now, my friend.

    This morning, rising early, I happened upon old poetry manuscripts stored in my desk. Among the pages lay the names of old companions and fellow travelers from years past. Half of them, I discovered, have already passed into the realm of ghosts. The rest are scattered across a thousand leagues, their voices lost to me—many now silent beyond all hearing. As I thought of them, I could not help but cry out in sudden grief.

    Among them were Hamsajin and O Deok-jeon and a few others besides—men I called friends, bound by affection that transcended age. Yet they too have all gone to their eternal rest. They were my elders, and this is only natural; yet this teaches us that even the young cannot rest assured. How fragile is the life of man! How terrifyingly brief!

    Alas—only you and I, thank Heaven, remain unharmed. Day after day we share each other's company, and between us there has never been rupture or estrangement. And yet, human life knows no constancy in its gatherings and dispersals. Today we meet; tomorrow, who knows where we shall go? Before that uncertain hour comes, let us simply strive to exhaust the pleasures that remain. What else matters to me but this?

    Recall when we drank at Magistrate Lee's house—such joy! I was carried home on another's arm, so deep was my intoxication. I remember nothing of what I said that night. Do you recall it? I remember only that halfway through my drunkenness, I called for a plain zither and played upon it. And those two evenings at the Clear Pavilion by the Jade Pool at Anhwa Temple—did you see how mad I became?

    Recently, my household has brewed new wine, fragrant and rich, worthy of drinking. How could I bear not to share it with you and the others? Moreover, the crimson apricot blossoms are just beginning to open, and the spring warmth brings such gentle enchantment—it stirs the heart and awakens deep feeling. On such a beautiful season, to not drink would be folly!

    I beg you to come and bring Magistrate Lee and Park Hwan-go with you. Otherwise, my wine will be exhausted in mere days! Should you visit later and find it gone, you will have only tea to console you.

    I am troubled and anxious. I bow my head before you.
  footnotes:
    - The title suggests this is a letter (手書) sent to 'Jeon Ryeo-ji' (全履之), likely a close friend of Lee Gyeo-bo.
    - The 'Clear Pavilion by the Jade Pool' (環碧亭清軒) at Anhwa Temple appears to be a favorite gathering place for the author and his circle of friends.
    - The phrase about 'water calamity' (水厄) is a playful pun—if the wine is gone, only tea (which requires water) will remain.
